        "My opponent leans heavily on the European experience, but that comparison cuts both ways. The countries that repealed wealth taxes did so largely because of EU capital mobility \u2014 wealthy individuals could simply move assets across open borders to lower-tax jurisdictions. The United States, which taxes based on citizenship rather than residency, faces a fundamentally different enforcement landscape. An American billionaire cannot simply move to Switzerland to escape U.S. taxation the way a French billionaire could move to Belgium. This structural difference makes the European repeal story far less relevant than opponents suggest.\n\nThe Switzerland example actually helps the case for a wealth tax. Switzerland has maintained its wealth tax continuously and generates meaningful revenue from it \u2014 up to 1% of GDP. Swiss cantons have developed sophisticated valuation methodologies for private businesses, real estate, and financial assets. The administrative challenges are real but solvable, as Switzerland has demonstrated for over a century. The \"impossibility\" of valuation is overstated: banks value these assets constantly for lending purposes, private equity firms mark portfolios to market quarterly, and the estate tax already requires comprehensive wealth valuation at death.\n\nOn the revenue estimates, even if Penn Wharton's lower figure of $2.1 trillion over ten years is correct, that is still $2.1 trillion that is currently going untaxed. And the macroeconomic effects Penn Wharton projects \u2014 a 3.1% smaller capital stock by 2050 \u2014 assume the revenue is simply removed from the economy rather than reinvested in public goods like infrastructure, education, and healthcare, which have their own growth-enhancing effects. The static analysis misses the dynamic benefits of reduced inequality, increased social mobility, and restored democratic legitimacy.\n\nMy opponent suggests alternatives like taxing capital gains at realization or ending stepped-up basis. I agree those reforms are also needed. But they do not address the fundamental problem: wealth compounds tax-free for decades while income is taxed annually. Only a wealth tax addresses the structural advantage of being rich in a system designed to make the rich richer.",
