      content:
        "The trajectory argument is decisive. Every space capability that exists today was once called impossible or impractical. Reusable rockets were dismissed until SpaceX proved them. Satellite internet was science fiction until Starlink served 4 million subscribers. The International Space Station \u2014 a permanent habitat in space \u2014 has been continuously occupied for 25 years. The question is not whether Mars settlement faces challenges, but whether those challenges are fundamentally unsolvable. Nothing my opponent has cited is a physics problem \u2014 they are engineering and cost problems, and those are exactly what iterative development solves.\n\nWaiting for Earth's problems to be solved before investing in Mars is like saying families shouldn't save for retirement until all bills are paid. There will never be a perfect time. The cost of inaction is existential: a single catastrophic event could end human civilization permanently. Mars settlement is the only technology that addresses species-level extinction risk. No amount of pandemic preparedness or asteroid deflection eliminates the risk entirely.\n\nThe priority question answers itself. Mars settlement requires precisely the technologies we need for Earth: better energy systems, closed-loop resource management, advanced agriculture, and radiation protection. It is not either/or. It is the most ambitious engineering challenge in history, and humanity's greatest achievements have always come from reaching beyond what seemed practical.",
