      content: "My opponent’s case conflates inequality with harm and then assumes billionaire wealth is mostly rent extraction. The literature is not that simple. Per Krusell and Anthony Smith’s Journal of Political Economy critique argues that Piketty’s second law rests on implausible saving assumptions, and Hubmer, Krusell, and Smith’s quantitative work finds the r minus g channel explains only a small part of recent U.S. wealth concentration. Just as important, William Nordhaus found that producers capture only a minuscule fraction of the social returns from technological change, meaning consumers receive most of the gains, and Samuel Kortum and Josh Lerner found venture capital accounts for a disproportionately large share of industrial innovation relative to its size. A fortune tied up in firm equity is often the residual of having created enormous consumer surplus, not proof that society has been pillaged.\n\nThe democracy argument is also overstated. Gilens and Page is influential, but later work does not justify treating oligarchy as a settled empirical fact. Branham, Soroka, and Wlezien found that rich and middle-income citizens usually agree and, when they disagree, the rich win only slightly more often. Across thirty European countries, Mikael Persson and Anders Sundell find only a slight edge for the rich, measured in a gap of a few percentage points, and no systematic relationship between unequal responsiveness and either economic inequality or campaign-finance regulation. Jeffrey Lax, Justin Phillips, and Adam Zelizer, in the American Political Science Review, put the point sharply: party trumps the purse. If the real problem is corruption, campaign finance, or partisan distortion, then the remedy is to fix those institutions directly, not to declare extreme wealth itself the disease.\n\nThe philanthropy objection misses the resolution. No serious negative case says philanthropy should replace democratic government. The question is whether society should prevent extreme fortunes from existing at all, even when they finance high-risk projects that states and electorates often underprovide. A 2021 Lancet modeling study estimated that vaccination against ten pathogens in 98 low- and middle-income countries averted 37 million deaths from 2000 to 2019, within a global health ecosystem financed by governments, Gavi, and large-scale philanthropy. That does not make billionaires saints, but it does show that concentrated private capital can generate public goods on a scale the affirmative simply dismisses.\n\nFinally, the policy mechanism is much weaker than the moral rhetoric. The OECD’s 2018 review concluded there are limited arguments for a recurrent net wealth tax on top of broad capital-income and inheritance taxes, and it specifically notes valuation problems, liquidity problems, and even regressive effects when actual returns differ across assets; it also argues inheritance taxes are less distortive if the concern is entrenched privilege across generations. The country evidence points the same way. Brülhart, Gruber, Krapf, and Schmidheiny find substantial behavioral responses and bunching under Swiss wealth taxation, while Jakobsen, Kleven, Kolsrud, Landais, and Muñoz find that a one-point increase in the top wealth-tax rate reduces the stock of wealthy taxpayers by about 2 percent and harms firms through owner out-migration. So even if we dislike monopoly, loopholes, or inherited advantage, the answer is targeted antitrust, better tax enforcement, and cleaner campaign rules, not a blanket principle that billionaire-level wealth is itself harmful and should be prevented.",
